libAMoRE++

http://libalf.informatik.rwth-aachen.de/

(c) 2008,2009,2010,2011
	Lehrstuhl Softwaremodellierung und Verifikation (I2), RWTH Aachen University
    and Lehrstuhl Logik und Theorie diskreter Systeme (I7), RWTH Aachen University
    and David R. Piegdon


libAMoRE++ is a C++ interface to libAMoRE, implementing several extensions
and additional functionality. most notably:

	* evaluating runs on automata, calculating predecessor and successor states
	* creating residual language automata
	* parsing and dumping automata to binary data
	  (libalf provides a human-readable converter)
	* efficient implementation of emtpyness-check
	* calculating a sample-word of a language (if not empty)
	* antichain algorithm for efficient checking of
	  language inclusion and language universality
	  (see "M. De Wulf, L. Doyen, J.-F. Raskin -
	   Antichains: A New Algorithm for Checking Universality of Finite Automata"

NOTE

if you want to use the statically linked libAMoRE and libAMoRE++, you will need
to link via:

	--start-group libAMoRE.a libAMoRE++.a --end-group

otherwise you will get an error about unresolved symbols due to circular
dependencies, because libAMoRE required the client application (in this case
libAMoRE++) to define some variables (see include/amore/vars.h).

